WEBVTT

00:04.743 --> 00:06.658
Your biological father
and I agreed

00:06.702 --> 00:08.312
that we would never
contact you.

00:08.356 --> 00:09.922
<i>I broke that agreement.</i>

00:09.966 --> 00:11.098
Maybe you could
just reach out

00:11.141 --> 00:12.490
and ask him if he'd like
to meet me.

00:12.534 --> 00:14.318
Vanessa...
I can try to find him.

00:14.362 --> 00:15.537
<i>The last time around</i>

00:15.580 --> 00:17.539
we got into some
pretty unhealthy patterns.

00:17.582 --> 00:19.845
I know
that we have history, Will,

00:19.889 --> 00:21.804
but it is history.

00:21.847 --> 00:23.284
<i>My units aren't</i> <i>
totally done yet.</i>

00:23.327 --> 00:25.112
Actually, one is livable.

00:25.155 --> 00:27.853
If you want it, it's yours.
- Thank you.

00:27.897 --> 00:29.072
Pamela, what's going on?

00:29.116 --> 00:31.074
<i>My hand at rest,</i> <i>
rock steady.</i>

00:31.118 --> 00:33.642
But when I pinch
my fingers together...

00:33.685 --> 00:35.513
there's something wrong
with my hand, Crockett.

00:35.557 --> 00:37.124
<i>I don't want to jeopardize</i> <i>
this investigation</i>

00:37.167 --> 00:38.821
because you can't handle
being in the dark.

00:38.864 --> 00:40.257
I care about you, Milena.

00:40.301 --> 00:42.607
I can't wait
for this case to be over.

00:42.651 --> 00:43.869
Yeah, me too.

00:43.913 --> 00:46.394
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

00:48.265 --> 00:51.138
<i>This is dispatch.</i> <i>
All teams report.</i>

00:51.181 --> 00:53.488
<i>What's your status?</i>

00:53.531 --> 00:55.316
<i>Team Charlie,</i> <i>
target house 28,</i>

00:55.359 --> 00:58.536
<i>offender in custody.</i>

00:58.580 --> 01:01.713
<i>Team Victor,</i> <i>
target 64 in custody.</i>

01:01.757 --> 01:04.890
<i>Team David,</i> <i>
target 52 in custody.</i>

01:04.934 --> 01:07.676
<i>[gunshots]</i> <i>
- Shots fired! Shots fired!</i>

01:07.719 --> 01:10.940
<i>10-1, 10-1!</i> <i>
Shots fired, target 16 house!</i>

01:10.983 --> 01:12.420
<i>Officer down! Roll an ambo!</i>

01:12.463 --> 01:16.337
<i>Stay with me, Sam.</i> <i>
Stay with me, Sa--</i>

01:16.380 --> 01:17.860
- I gotta go see what's up.
- No, you're undercover.

01:17.903 --> 01:19.079
You're not supposed to be
involved with this.

01:19.122 --> 01:20.210
Doesn't matter. Just go.

01:20.254 --> 01:22.691
You gotta get to the hospital,
okay?

01:22.734 --> 01:25.650
<i>[tense music]</i>

01:25.694 --> 01:32.440
<i>♪</i>

01:34.006 --> 01:36.705
[knocks]
Morning.

01:36.748 --> 01:38.359
- Morning.
- Thought I'd drop this off

01:38.402 --> 01:40.012
before I do some consults.

01:40.056 --> 01:41.492
- Thank you.
- Yeah.

01:41.536 --> 01:44.452
- Got my MRI.
- Oh, great.

01:48.717 --> 01:51.676
Progressive cervical
spondylotic myelopathy.

01:51.720 --> 01:55.202
- You're gonna need surgery.
- I don't think I will.

01:55.245 --> 01:57.291
What are you talking about?
This is...

01:57.334 --> 01:59.771
this is serious.
It's--it's spinal compression.

01:59.815 --> 02:03.514
I'm doing physical therapy.
I'll work through it.

02:03.558 --> 02:05.125
[scoffs]

02:07.823 --> 02:09.825
Recovery from surgery
is six to eight weeks,

02:09.868 --> 02:11.957
and I've got a patient list
a mile long.

02:12.001 --> 02:14.308
I--

02:14.351 --> 02:16.832
I can't leave them
for that amount of time.

02:16.875 --> 02:19.400
[sighs]
You might want another opinion.

02:21.315 --> 02:24.318
I'm happy
with the one I have.

02:24.361 --> 02:30.237
<i>♪</i>

02:30.280 --> 02:32.152
Okay.

02:35.590 --> 02:37.418
Hey, Dylan,
got one coming in.

02:37.461 --> 02:39.420
Juliette, I'm going to Baghdad.

02:39.463 --> 02:42.249
CPD Sam Devers, 45,
shot through and through,

02:42.292 --> 02:43.772
right lateral chest
to right back.

02:43.815 --> 02:45.208
Bullet was retrieved
from the back of his vest.

02:45.252 --> 02:47.950
BP 98/66, heart rate 92.

02:47.993 --> 02:50.300
Hey, Sam, I'm Dr. Choi.
This is Dr. Scott.

02:50.344 --> 02:51.823
- What happened?
- Drug raid.

02:51.867 --> 02:53.695
Guys were waiting for us.

02:53.738 --> 02:55.740
Ambush.

02:55.784 --> 03:02.704
<i>♪</i>

03:09.972 --> 03:11.930
All right, let's roll him.

03:11.974 --> 03:14.281
All right, ready? Roll.

03:14.324 --> 03:16.108
- [groans]
- All right, I'm seeing

03:16.152 --> 03:17.762
two wounds,
probably an entry and exit.

03:17.806 --> 03:20.591
Back.
- [groaning]

03:20.635 --> 03:23.246
Sam? Sam! Oh, my God!

03:23.290 --> 03:26.118
Are you all right?
- It's okay, Alice.

03:26.162 --> 03:28.599
I'm sure it'll be fine.
- It is not fine.

03:28.643 --> 03:30.688
You got shot!
- Please, ma'am,

03:30.732 --> 03:31.907
if you wouldn't mind
waiting outside, we--

03:31.950 --> 03:33.169
I'm his wife.
I'm not going anywhere.

03:33.213 --> 03:36.085
All right, everyone clear
for an X-ray.

03:36.128 --> 03:39.349
Clear.
[machinery beeping]

03:39.393 --> 03:40.872
Hemothorax on the right.

03:40.916 --> 03:44.006
All right, let's set him up
for a chest tube.

03:44.049 --> 03:46.661
You only saw one entry wound
and one exit wound, right?

03:46.704 --> 03:48.140
Yeah.

03:48.184 --> 03:50.230
There's a bullet here
in his right hilum.

03:50.273 --> 03:51.927
Sam, you ever been shot
before?

03:51.970 --> 03:54.625
- Uh-uh, no.
- You sure?

03:54.669 --> 03:55.626
Yeah.

03:55.670 --> 03:58.281
<i>[tense music]</i>

03:58.325 --> 04:00.283
You know, it's
that new seafood place

04:00.327 --> 04:03.025
on the river.
It's got a huge lobster tank.

04:03.068 --> 04:06.637
So you want me to pick out
an animal and then eat it?

04:06.681 --> 04:08.160
I'm sure you could get
a salad.

04:08.204 --> 04:10.859
Hey, Dad, I think
you might need this today.

04:10.902 --> 04:12.469
Oh, my God.

04:12.513 --> 04:13.818
Honey...
- Yeah.

04:13.862 --> 04:15.472
Thank you so much.

04:15.516 --> 04:17.431
Um...

04:17.474 --> 04:20.521
this is my colleague,
Dr. Richardson.

04:20.564 --> 04:22.479
My daughter Anna.

04:22.523 --> 04:23.872
We've--we've met.

04:23.915 --> 04:26.875
We did the family therapy,
remember?

04:26.918 --> 04:28.137
Of course we did.

04:28.180 --> 04:29.747
- Yeah.
- That's right.

04:29.791 --> 04:32.228
It's nice to see you again, Anna.

04:32.272 --> 04:35.231
Um, anyways, I am late
for first period, so.

04:35.275 --> 04:37.929
Thank you, honey.
Thanks again.

04:37.973 --> 04:39.366
[scoffs]
Jesus.

04:39.409 --> 04:42.804
So does she not know?

04:42.847 --> 04:45.937
About us?

04:45.981 --> 04:47.461
You know, I guess
she doesn't.

04:47.504 --> 04:52.596
Um, I guess I haven't found
the right time to tell her?

04:52.640 --> 04:55.338
Is that really it, Daniel?

04:55.382 --> 04:56.861
What do you mean?

04:56.905 --> 04:58.863
Well, sometimes you try
to protect the people you love

04:58.907 --> 05:01.083
by avoiding
difficult conversations

05:01.126 --> 05:03.607
with them.
- Ahh.

05:03.651 --> 05:06.001
Benefits of dating your shrink.

05:06.044 --> 05:10.005
Um, no, that's not
what's going on.

05:10.048 --> 05:12.050
Anyway, I gotta get upstairs.

05:12.094 --> 05:13.965
So seafood tomorrow night?
We on?

05:14.009 --> 05:15.967
- Sounds perfect.
- Nice.

05:16.011 --> 05:18.927
<i>[apprehensive music]</i>

05:18.970 --> 05:23.366
<i>♪</i>

05:23.410 --> 05:25.237
Hey.

05:25.281 --> 05:26.978
Those plants you got
for the building?

05:27.022 --> 05:29.329
Nice!
- Thanks.

05:29.372 --> 05:31.113
Six is good.

05:31.156 --> 05:34.116
Did you know peace lilies
actually absorb sound?

05:34.159 --> 05:37.728
Yeah, I'm trying
to cut down on street noise.

05:37.772 --> 05:39.469
Look at you, Mr. Google.

05:39.513 --> 05:41.471
Hey, I have to ask, I noticed
that you haven't cashed

05:41.515 --> 05:44.735
my rent check yet.

05:44.779 --> 05:48.826
Well, I--
no, uh, I didn't.

05:48.870 --> 05:50.785
Well, how come?

05:52.700 --> 05:54.179
Actually, it bounced.

05:54.223 --> 05:55.790
- Why didn't you tell me?
- It's no big deal.

05:55.833 --> 05:59.402
Of course it's a big deal.
I'm good for it.

05:59.446 --> 06:01.926
- You know--
- Dr. Halstead? Dr. Asher?

06:01.970 --> 06:03.014
I'm having trouble getting
a visitor

06:03.058 --> 06:04.407
to leave a patient's room.

06:04.451 --> 06:08.324
- What's the problem?
- It's the patient's mom.

06:08.368 --> 06:11.153
We'll be right there, thanks.

06:11.196 --> 06:14.635
Hi, I'm Dr. Halstead
and this is Dr. Asher, OB-GYN.

06:14.678 --> 06:16.941
How can we help you?
- Well...

06:16.985 --> 06:18.943
tell them, Mom,
how I'm a total failure.

06:18.987 --> 06:21.119
I am 22, single, and pregnant.

06:21.163 --> 06:22.469
Yes, she's pregnant.

06:22.512 --> 06:24.775
She shouldn't be working
as a hot yoga instructor.

06:24.819 --> 06:26.429
She passed out.

06:26.473 --> 06:27.604
You see?
It--it's always the same.

06:27.648 --> 06:30.172
I just can't do anything right.

06:30.215 --> 06:32.000
I just want her to leave.

06:32.043 --> 06:33.305
Do you mind?

06:33.349 --> 06:34.959
Trini can take you
somewhere comfortable

06:35.003 --> 06:37.527
while we speak
with your daughter.

06:37.571 --> 06:40.225
I'll be waiting outside.

06:40.269 --> 06:44.055
[sighs]
I'm sorry.

06:44.099 --> 06:47.407
Anyway, um, I'm Kat.
I'm 26 weeks along.

06:47.450 --> 06:49.060
Hi, Kat.
So what happened today?

06:49.104 --> 06:51.062
You passed out?

06:51.106 --> 06:53.848
I got a little dizzy,
and then, yeah.

06:53.891 --> 06:56.111
Has this happened before?

06:56.154 --> 06:58.287
I guess I haven't really
been myself lately.

06:58.330 --> 07:01.159
Like, I've been nauseous, swollen,

07:01.203 --> 07:02.987
feeling pretty run-down.

07:03.031 --> 07:05.163
Um, it's a little worse today,

07:05.207 --> 07:07.862
but it's just
normal pregnancy stuff.

07:07.905 --> 07:09.559
Maybe.

07:09.603 --> 07:12.432
Though it is a bit late for you
to still be getting nauseous.

07:12.475 --> 07:16.174
Yeah, and your blood pressure
and temp are a little high.

07:16.218 --> 07:19.351
- Are you concerned?
- Not necessarily.

07:19.395 --> 07:20.570
But we would like
to get an ultrasound

07:20.614 --> 07:23.530
and run a few tests.

07:23.573 --> 07:25.096
- Okay.
- Just give us a little time

07:25.140 --> 07:26.663
to get some answers, kay?

07:26.707 --> 07:31.189
<i>♪</i>

07:31.233 --> 07:35.063
Oh, and, um, my mom?

07:35.106 --> 07:36.456
Would you like me to get her?

07:39.850 --> 07:41.417
No. No.

07:46.901 --> 07:48.598
Hi, Ms. Reed.
I'm Dr. Taylor.

07:48.642 --> 07:49.947
Hi, nice to meet you.

07:49.991 --> 07:52.646
Lydia choked
on some cereal this morning.

07:52.689 --> 07:54.996
I still feel like there's
something in there.

07:55.039 --> 07:56.214
I'm sorry.

07:56.258 --> 07:58.216
Uh, has this happened
to you before?

07:58.260 --> 08:00.436
Uh, I thought I got a--

08:00.480 --> 08:04.962
a doxycycline pill, uh,
stuck a few weeks ago.

08:05.006 --> 08:07.095
I was taking it
for Lyme disease.

08:07.138 --> 08:09.619
Okay, um, how long ago
did you have that?

08:09.663 --> 08:11.795
Turns out I didn't.
[chuckles weakly]

08:11.839 --> 08:14.798
I also didn't have fibromyalgia

08:14.842 --> 08:18.149
or MS or chronic fatigue.

08:18.193 --> 08:19.716
[clears throat]

08:19.760 --> 08:22.980
You see enough specialists,
you get a pretty good list.

08:23.024 --> 08:24.068
Can I ask
what was going on

08:24.112 --> 08:25.417
that made you see
all these doctors?

08:25.461 --> 08:28.246
Well, um,
a year and a half ago,

08:28.290 --> 08:30.901
- I--I--
- I got an--an eye twitch.

08:30.945 --> 08:32.990
Uh, and I thought,

08:33.034 --> 08:36.298
"Lydia, you are giving
200 talks a year."

08:36.341 --> 08:40.215
I'm a motivational speaker.
"You're just tired."

08:40.258 --> 08:45.350
But then my best friend
got diagnosed with ALS.

08:45.394 --> 08:48.615
Scariest thing ever.
So I went to a neurologist,

08:48.658 --> 08:50.965
but he ruled ALS out.

08:51.008 --> 08:53.315
- That's good.
- Right.

08:53.358 --> 08:57.537
But then I got coughing fits,
then stiffness...

08:57.580 --> 09:00.191
[clears throat]
Then exhaustion.

09:00.235 --> 09:02.585
And nobody could figure it out.

09:02.629 --> 09:04.369
Here I am.

09:04.413 --> 09:05.849
Well, hopefully, we'll
be able to help you today.

09:05.893 --> 09:07.503
If it's okay, I'd like to order
some more bloodwork.

09:07.547 --> 09:09.200
- Yes.
- And in the meantime,

09:09.244 --> 09:10.550
I'm gonna take a closer look
at your throat.

09:10.593 --> 09:12.377
- Okay.
- Prep pharyngoscope?

09:12.421 --> 09:14.641
And a CBC, CMP, and ANA.

09:14.684 --> 09:16.033
You got it.

09:16.077 --> 09:19.080
I'll be right back.

09:19.123 --> 09:21.343
Hey, Mags?
- Mm-hmm?

09:21.386 --> 09:22.866
Were you able
to track down any info

09:22.910 --> 09:24.738
on my biological father?

09:24.781 --> 09:27.218
Oh, no.
I wasn't able to find anything.

09:27.262 --> 09:29.873
But, um, I'll keep trying.

09:29.917 --> 09:31.440
Okay.

09:33.311 --> 09:35.618
Morning, Maggie.

09:35.662 --> 09:37.968
Oh, hey, Sharon.

09:38.012 --> 09:40.536
Uh-oh. What's up?

09:40.580 --> 09:42.886
[sighs]

09:42.930 --> 09:44.801
Vanessa keeps asking
about her biological father,

09:44.845 --> 09:46.890
and I promised her I would try
and get in touch with him,

09:46.934 --> 09:50.154
but I haven't.
- Oh.

09:50.198 --> 09:51.373
It's been over 20 years.

09:51.416 --> 09:53.636
I don't want
to disrupt his life.

09:53.680 --> 09:58.641
But it's what Vanessa wants,
and I want to be fair to her.

09:58.685 --> 10:01.209
- Good morning, Ben.
- Sharon, nice to see you.

10:01.252 --> 10:02.471
Good to see you.

10:02.514 --> 10:04.995
Oh, walking is something
out there.

10:05.039 --> 10:07.171
Coffee after my checkup?
- Yeah, you bet.

10:07.215 --> 10:09.347
All right.

10:09.391 --> 10:13.482
Look, I know
that Ben wasn't so keen

10:13.525 --> 10:15.092
on you getting in touch
with Vanessa

10:15.136 --> 10:16.354
in the first place,

10:16.398 --> 10:19.444
but have you discussed this
with him?

10:19.488 --> 10:20.532
No!

10:20.576 --> 10:23.971
- Maggie--
- Sharon, no.

10:24.014 --> 10:26.364
Hey, where's Sam?

10:26.408 --> 10:28.932
Uh, just sent him to IR
for an embolization.

10:28.976 --> 10:30.020
Why?
Bullet tract went

10:30.064 --> 10:31.065
straight through the lung.

10:31.108 --> 10:32.240
The chest tube took care
of that.

10:32.283 --> 10:34.546
Yeah, but look...

10:34.590 --> 10:36.636
the bullet we saw on the x-ray
caused a pseudoaneurysm

10:36.679 --> 10:38.333
in a branch
of the pulmonary artery.

10:38.376 --> 10:40.683
That thing could have blown anytime.

10:40.727 --> 10:43.251
You know, Sam said
he never got shot before,

10:43.294 --> 10:44.339
so he must have got hit
twice today,

10:44.382 --> 10:45.819
just didn't realize it.

10:45.862 --> 10:47.559
And we're missing
the other entry wound.

10:47.603 --> 10:48.865
There's a lot
of air pockets and scatter

10:48.909 --> 10:50.693
all over that CT.

10:50.737 --> 10:53.696
Hmm.

10:53.740 --> 10:57.700
- I--
- I've got an idea how we might know for sure.

10:57.744 --> 10:59.876
The thing
about bodycam footage

10:59.920 --> 11:03.053
is it's all live and unedited,
so it can get kind of violent.

11:03.097 --> 11:05.534
You guys okay?
both: Yeah.

11:05.577 --> 11:08.145
- Thanks, man.
- You got it, Doc.

11:08.189 --> 11:11.279
<i>Chicago Police,</i> <i>
search warrant.</i>

11:11.322 --> 11:12.323
<i>- Go, go, go!</i> <i>
- Police! Don't move!</i>

11:12.367 --> 11:13.716
<i>Drop the gun. Drop it!</i>

11:13.760 --> 11:14.804
<i>[officers shouting]</i>

11:14.848 --> 11:15.979
<i>[gunshot]</i>

11:16.023 --> 11:17.415
There--that looks like
the shot

11:17.459 --> 11:19.722
that came out the other side
I found in his vest.

11:19.766 --> 11:21.332
<i>- You all right, Sam?</i> <i>
- Alice, Alice!</i>

11:21.376 --> 11:22.812
<i>- Stay here, stay here.</i> <i>
- Call Alice.</i>

11:22.856 --> 11:25.423
<i>10-1, 10-1!</i> <i>
Shots fired, target 16 house!</i>

11:25.467 --> 11:28.078
So does he get hit again?

11:28.122 --> 11:29.776
Can you run it back slowly?

11:29.819 --> 11:31.081
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

11:31.125 --> 11:34.345
<i>[gunshot echoes</i> <i>
in slow motion]</i>

11:34.389 --> 11:35.520
<i>Put your hands up!</i> <i>
Put your hands up!</i>

11:35.564 --> 11:37.044
<i>Walk towards me! Drop the gun!</i>

11:37.087 --> 11:40.351
<i>Come here! Get on the ground!</i> <i>
Get on the ground!</i>

11:40.395 --> 11:42.484
No, just the one shot.

11:42.527 --> 11:44.007
[sighs]

11:44.051 --> 11:46.575
So if that bullet we just saw
was the one we recovered,

11:46.618 --> 11:49.230
where did the one in his lung
come from?

11:49.273 --> 11:51.232
Didn't get it here.

11:51.275 --> 11:55.279
<i>♪</i>

12:00.067 --> 12:01.546
- Hey.
- Hi.

12:01.590 --> 12:03.070
Just saw Mr. Stevens.

12:03.113 --> 12:05.028
Two days post-op,
incision's looking good.

12:05.072 --> 12:07.074
- Yeah.
- Your button.

12:07.117 --> 12:09.119
- Hmm?
- Your button.

12:09.163 --> 12:11.948
Oh. It's fine.

12:11.992 --> 12:13.950
I should put on
some scrubs anyway.

12:13.994 --> 12:15.822
Hey, wait a second.

12:20.000 --> 12:22.132
You can't button it, can you?

12:22.176 --> 12:26.310
- Crocket...
- Pamela, you can't operate.

12:26.354 --> 12:27.616
Not like this.

12:27.659 --> 12:28.660
You know I'd never do anything

12:28.704 --> 12:30.227
to endanger my patients.

12:30.271 --> 12:33.404
Yeah, well I have to question
your judgement on this.

12:33.448 --> 12:36.320
You cannot do surgery.

12:36.364 --> 12:38.932
It isn't safe.

12:38.975 --> 12:42.413
- Are you serious?
- Yeah.

12:42.457 --> 12:45.808
<i>[apprehensive music]</i>

12:45.852 --> 12:50.726
<i>♪</i>

12:50.770 --> 12:52.989
So your embolization
went well,

12:53.033 --> 12:54.861
though it was
a little more complicated

12:54.904 --> 12:56.340
than expected.

12:56.384 --> 12:57.777
The radiologist noted

12:57.820 --> 12:59.343
that the bullet
had been eroding

12:59.387 --> 13:01.215
into the vessel wall
for some time.

13:01.258 --> 13:02.564
Apparently,
when your lung collapsed

13:02.607 --> 13:04.696
and reinflated again,
the movement was enough

13:04.740 --> 13:07.264
to make the situation emergent.

13:07.308 --> 13:11.834
On closer examination,
we noticed a faint scar

13:11.878 --> 13:13.749
indicating
an old gunshot wound.

13:15.185 --> 13:17.753
It's pretty clear to us
you've been shot before.

13:19.755 --> 13:21.583
Yeah, I was.

13:21.626 --> 13:23.628
Doc said it was 50/50
to take it out or not--

13:23.672 --> 13:25.456
- You never told me?
- Alice--

13:25.500 --> 13:26.631
Sam, I'm sorry.

13:26.675 --> 13:28.024
I was just trying
to make her feel better.

13:28.068 --> 13:29.939
You know how you were okay
the last time.

13:29.983 --> 13:31.941
You told them you were shot.
They all know everything,

13:31.985 --> 13:35.118
but you couldn't tell me?
- I didn't want to worry you.

13:37.904 --> 13:39.209
Let his friends
come sit with him.

13:39.253 --> 13:40.602
They're all
he cares about anyway.

13:40.645 --> 13:42.604
Alice!
[grunts]

13:42.647 --> 13:47.391
<i>♪</i>

13:47.435 --> 13:49.785
You do have
some redness and irritation,

13:49.829 --> 13:51.569
but I don't see
any foreign bodies.

13:51.613 --> 13:53.310
Your labs are normal,
so if you're feeling better,

13:53.354 --> 13:55.008
I feel comfortable
sending you home.

13:57.184 --> 13:58.489
Lydia?

14:00.927 --> 14:02.102
Lydia!

14:02.145 --> 14:03.625
I just don't know
what's wrong with me.

14:03.668 --> 14:07.585
All I do is go to doctors,
and no one has any answers.

14:07.629 --> 14:08.935
- - I'm--
- I'm sorry.

14:08.978 --> 14:10.980
I used to travel
around the country,

14:11.024 --> 14:13.417
speaking and helping people.

14:13.461 --> 14:15.767
And now there are days
I don't even get out of bed.

14:15.811 --> 14:17.726
- Here, here.
- [sobs]

14:17.769 --> 14:19.510
- Here, take one.
- [coughs]

14:19.554 --> 14:22.905
[sobbing]
- Okay.

14:22.949 --> 14:24.428
Is there anything else
I can get you?

14:24.472 --> 14:25.821
Maybe water?

14:32.654 --> 14:34.003
No.

14:36.484 --> 14:37.964
I'm okay.

14:39.922 --> 14:41.402
Okay, um...

14:41.445 --> 14:42.925
you know, let me speak
with one of my colleagues

14:42.969 --> 14:44.622
and see if we can figure
something out.

14:44.666 --> 14:51.629
<i>♪</i>

14:51.673 --> 14:53.240
Dr. Charles?

14:53.283 --> 14:55.242
I have a patient
who's been to a lot of doctors

14:55.285 --> 14:56.983
for some pretty vague symptoms.

14:57.026 --> 14:59.899
Her labs and exam
are all normal.

14:59.942 --> 15:02.075
But she just got
extremely upset just now

15:02.118 --> 15:04.294
when I told her
that I couldn't find anything.

15:04.338 --> 15:05.687
I don't know,
something about it

15:05.730 --> 15:08.298
just feels a little off.
- Okay.

15:08.342 --> 15:10.910
How can I help?
- I don't know.

15:10.953 --> 15:13.913
The long history,
the multiple diagnoses,

15:13.956 --> 15:15.958
she--she could be malingering?

15:16.002 --> 15:18.352
Do you mind talking to her?
- No.

15:18.395 --> 15:21.964
Shoot me her chart?
- Okay.

15:22.008 --> 15:23.531
Well, labs don't show much,

15:23.574 --> 15:25.837
but her pressure's
still creeping up.

15:25.881 --> 15:27.752
Think this could be
pre-eclampsia?

15:27.796 --> 15:30.320
Could be,
but her LFT levels

15:30.364 --> 15:33.628
are slightly elevated
and her glucose is low.

15:35.325 --> 15:36.979
I'm wondering
if this actually might be

15:37.023 --> 15:39.373
acute fatty liver of pregnancy.

15:39.416 --> 15:41.418
If AFLP is even
on the table...

15:41.462 --> 15:42.985
I mean, missing it
would be catastrophic.

15:43.029 --> 15:45.466
Yeah.
We need to know for sure.

15:45.509 --> 15:47.076
Can you get this
up to Abrams for me?

15:47.120 --> 15:48.208
Thank you.
- Crockett...

15:48.251 --> 15:49.818
- Yeah?
- Got a minute?

15:49.861 --> 15:51.167
Yeah, what do you need?

15:51.211 --> 15:53.561
A liver biopsy
to check for AFLP.

15:55.476 --> 15:57.608
Okay, but if it is,
you do realize

15:57.652 --> 15:59.610
that the biopsy site
could bleed considerably.

15:59.654 --> 16:00.785
Yeah, we need an answer.

16:00.829 --> 16:02.004
If it's just pre-eclampsia,

16:02.048 --> 16:03.440
we'll keep the baby in
as long as we can.

16:03.484 --> 16:04.876
But if it is AFLP,

16:04.920 --> 16:06.574
the only cure is to deliver it.

16:06.617 --> 16:08.054
And if you watch and wait?

16:08.097 --> 16:09.707
There's a chance that
it could all work out fine.

16:09.751 --> 16:12.014
But there's also a chance
that the baby, and even Mom,

16:12.058 --> 16:14.799
could die.
We need this biopsy.

16:14.843 --> 16:16.236
[sighs]
Right.

16:16.279 --> 16:18.412
I don't know.
I'm not liking the choices.

16:20.153 --> 16:21.937
Crockett,
Dr. Asher needs the biopsy.

16:21.981 --> 16:23.634
I think Dr. Marcel heard me.

16:26.594 --> 16:28.335
Okay. I'll set it up.

16:28.378 --> 16:29.684
- Great.
- You got it.

16:29.727 --> 16:31.251
Thank you.

16:33.644 --> 16:34.950
Hannah.

16:37.735 --> 16:39.259
Hannah!

16:39.302 --> 16:42.610
Why do you constantly feel
the need to save me, Will?

16:42.653 --> 16:44.003
Save you?

16:44.046 --> 16:46.744
What you just did
with Crockett.

16:46.788 --> 16:48.398
Not telling me about the check?

16:48.442 --> 16:50.792
Whoa, I--
hey, I'm just trying to help.

16:50.835 --> 16:52.359
Really, Will?

16:52.402 --> 16:53.316
Or is it because
you don't think

16:53.360 --> 16:56.015
I can take care of myself?

16:56.058 --> 16:58.452
No matter what I do,
you are still stuck

16:58.495 --> 17:00.584
on how you thought about me
two years ago.

17:00.628 --> 17:02.543
I want to support you.

17:02.586 --> 17:03.587
I don't want to derail

17:03.631 --> 17:05.024
all the hard work
that you've done.

17:05.067 --> 17:08.679
That is my responsibility,
not yours.

17:15.295 --> 17:16.426
I gotta tell you,
I don't think

17:16.470 --> 17:19.081
she's malingering.
- Really?

17:19.125 --> 17:21.040
But she's seen every specialist
in Chicago.

17:21.083 --> 17:22.563
Yeah, but true malingering,

17:22.606 --> 17:24.086
I mean, at least
from a clinical standpoint,

17:24.130 --> 17:26.436
would mean that she was
making up

17:26.480 --> 17:28.090
or exaggerating symptoms
for some kind

17:28.134 --> 17:30.701
of secondary gain, right?

17:30.745 --> 17:32.007
Like drug-seeking

17:32.051 --> 17:33.443
or because she didn't want
to go to work.

17:33.487 --> 17:34.836
You know, I'm just not
picking that up.

17:34.879 --> 17:36.098
I think she really wants
an answer.

17:36.142 --> 17:37.143
What if there isn't one?

17:37.186 --> 17:38.405
All of her tests
came back negative.

17:38.448 --> 17:39.754
Well, maybe you have
to keep on digging.

17:39.797 --> 17:42.278
Have you thought about,
I don't know,

17:42.322 --> 17:45.847
a lumbar puncture
or an endocrine panel?

17:45.890 --> 17:47.631
Yeah, yeah, okay.

17:47.675 --> 17:50.025
But the history
of doctor shopping,

17:50.069 --> 17:51.244
and that meltdown before...

17:51.287 --> 17:53.463
ugh, I don't know.

17:53.507 --> 17:55.639
I'd also like to give her
a psychiatric questionnaire.

17:55.683 --> 17:56.814
Just to make sure
we're not missing anything.

17:56.858 --> 17:58.816
Okay.
Let me, uh, know

17:58.860 --> 18:00.557
what you find out.
- Okay.

18:06.041 --> 18:08.652
[vending machine beeping]

18:11.438 --> 18:15.442
Excuse me, uh, but I know
an officer involved

18:15.485 --> 18:18.097
with the raids this morning.

18:18.140 --> 18:19.315
Any word on any other injuries?

18:19.359 --> 18:20.534
Details are sketchy,

18:20.577 --> 18:23.885
but it's still dangerous
out there.

18:23.928 --> 18:26.322
Hey, you got a name?

18:26.366 --> 18:30.152
Actually, no.
They're undercover.

18:30.196 --> 18:31.284
Well, I'll keep my ears open,

18:31.327 --> 18:33.938
let you know
if I hear anything.

18:33.982 --> 18:37.028
<i>[apprehensive music]</i>

18:37.072 --> 18:40.554
Dr. Scott. How's Sam?

18:40.597 --> 18:43.426
He's stable,
but it's still too early

18:43.470 --> 18:45.036
to tell
if the procedure worked.

18:45.080 --> 18:48.170
Dr. Scott? We need you.

18:48.214 --> 18:50.041
<i>[tense music]</i>

18:50.085 --> 18:52.348
[alarm beeping]

18:52.392 --> 18:53.654
His chest tube's
putting out blood.

18:53.697 --> 18:55.612
The embolization plug
must have dislodged.

18:55.656 --> 18:57.571
I need two units of blood
and FFP.

18:57.614 --> 18:59.138
Tell CT we're coming up.
- All right.

18:59.181 --> 19:00.356
Oh, my God.

19:00.400 --> 19:03.490
BP's down to 78/52.
Pulse is thready.

19:03.533 --> 19:05.753
He's in V-fib.
Charge the paddles to 200.

19:05.796 --> 19:08.103
Sam?

19:08.147 --> 19:09.887
- Charged.
- Clear.

19:09.931 --> 19:11.889
[monitor beeping]

19:11.933 --> 19:13.195
Sinus rhythm.

19:13.239 --> 19:14.718
All right, BP's good.

19:14.762 --> 19:17.112
Let's get him up to the ICU.
We'll stabilize him there.

19:20.811 --> 19:23.771
I'm in. Go.

19:23.814 --> 19:25.903
Come on. Move, move, move.

19:25.947 --> 19:27.166
Back up, back up.

19:27.209 --> 19:30.343
<i>♪</i>

19:37.741 --> 19:41.180
- Hey, I got your message.
- Hey, Sharon.

19:42.877 --> 19:48.491
When I told you about
Vanessa's biological father,

19:48.535 --> 19:51.451
there was a part I left out.

19:51.494 --> 19:57.239
I loved him at the time... deeply.

19:57.283 --> 20:00.503
Okay.

20:00.547 --> 20:02.070
But my life
is great right now.

20:02.113 --> 20:04.812
Ben is great.

20:04.855 --> 20:07.989
But this man, Grant,

20:08.032 --> 20:12.689
if I see him again,
I'm afraid--

20:12.733 --> 20:14.343
I'm afraid
of what I might feel.

20:14.387 --> 20:16.693
<i>[pensive music]</i>

20:16.737 --> 20:18.086
What happens
if those old feelings

20:18.129 --> 20:20.219
are still there?

20:20.262 --> 20:22.395
And what happens
when he sees Vanessa?

20:22.438 --> 20:24.092
Our perfect daughter?

20:26.660 --> 20:28.227
Sharon, I'm lost.

20:30.272 --> 20:33.014
Maggie...

20:33.057 --> 20:36.235
I wish I could tell you
what to do.

20:36.278 --> 20:38.237
I can't.

20:38.280 --> 20:42.719
But it does sound to me
like you're already thinking

20:42.763 --> 20:45.418
ten steps ahead.

20:45.461 --> 20:48.943
Whatever you decide,
it'll come from the heart.

20:48.986 --> 20:51.859
And that's the best
any of us can do.

20:53.643 --> 20:56.124
Yeah?

20:56.167 --> 20:57.734
Yeah.

20:57.778 --> 21:04.611
<i>♪</i>

21:10.138 --> 21:13.097
Uh, Afra, can you put
pressure on that for me?

21:13.141 --> 21:15.404
You got it?

21:15.448 --> 21:17.276
Hey, guys?
- Hmm.

21:17.319 --> 21:19.408
So the biopsy site's
still bleeding.

21:19.452 --> 21:22.281
If I can't get it to stop,
I'm gonna have to coil it.

21:22.324 --> 21:23.282
Path results.

21:23.325 --> 21:25.719
<i>[tense music]</i>

21:25.762 --> 21:28.765
Okay, we need
to deliver her now.

21:28.809 --> 21:30.593
Hey, Kat,
we've got some bad news.

21:30.637 --> 21:31.855
Unfortunately,
you have a condition

21:31.899 --> 21:33.857
called acute fatty liver
of pregnancy.

21:33.901 --> 21:35.294
It's an enzyme deficiency
that causes

21:35.337 --> 21:37.165
rapid and life-threatening
liver failure.

21:37.208 --> 21:40.124
- Oh, my God.
- We need to do a C-section.

21:40.168 --> 21:41.430
Okay, let's get
the hybrid OR ready.

21:41.474 --> 21:42.649
What? No. No, you can't.

21:42.692 --> 21:44.738
It's too soon.
- The baby is viable.

21:44.781 --> 21:46.435
We don't have
any other options.

21:46.479 --> 21:48.524
- Okay.
- Okay, ready?

21:48.568 --> 21:51.048
Let's go.

21:51.092 --> 21:53.094
Kat, what's going on?

21:53.137 --> 21:54.269
Mom, they have to deliver
the baby.

21:54.313 --> 21:55.749
- What?
- This is really serious.

21:55.792 --> 21:57.533
I'm scared.
Can she come with me?

21:57.577 --> 21:59.666
You can stay right outside.

21:59.709 --> 22:01.494
She'll be right outside.

22:01.537 --> 22:05.802
<i>♪</i>

22:05.846 --> 22:07.108
I'm not gonna do these.

22:07.151 --> 22:08.718
You already sent
that shrink in.

22:08.762 --> 22:11.068
- It--
- I'm not crazy.

22:11.112 --> 22:12.853
No, I don't think that.
I just want to check--

22:12.896 --> 22:14.811
Why won't someone
take me seriously?

22:14.855 --> 22:16.813
W--what kind of doctors
are you?

22:16.857 --> 22:18.467
- Lydia--
- I am sick, damn it.

22:18.511 --> 22:20.251
I am sick. Okay?

22:20.295 --> 22:22.123
There--there is
something wrong with me.

22:22.166 --> 22:23.342
Lydia, please,
I just want to help.

22:23.385 --> 22:25.648
But you're not. You're not.
No one is.

22:25.692 --> 22:27.824
- [gasps]
- No one is!

22:29.391 --> 22:34.570
- I am--I--
- I am so--so-- I'm so sorry.

22:34.614 --> 22:37.138
Lydia, what's going on?

22:37.181 --> 22:40.489
I don't know
why this keeps happening.

22:40.533 --> 22:43.884
Well, what keeps happening?

22:43.927 --> 22:47.017
I've been so e--
emotional lately.

22:47.061 --> 22:49.672
And it--it--
it just comes over me.

22:49.716 --> 22:51.674
Right.
A--and when that happens,

22:51.718 --> 22:53.502
what--how do you experience it?

22:53.546 --> 22:56.505
W--what does it feel like?

22:56.549 --> 22:57.985
I don't know.

22:58.028 --> 23:01.641
It's, like, so much feeling,

23:01.684 --> 23:05.079
and, um, it's--
it's overwhelming.

23:05.122 --> 23:06.123
Right.

23:06.167 --> 23:08.430
But then it suddenly just ends?

23:08.474 --> 23:10.824
Like someone hit a switch.

23:10.867 --> 23:13.392
Okay, um,
could you give me a moment?

23:15.568 --> 23:18.658
It--it--it's gotta be
psychiatric, right?

23:18.701 --> 23:21.574
Actually,
these emotional outbursts

23:21.617 --> 23:23.706
are making me think
it could be just the opposite.

23:23.750 --> 23:25.534
I'll be right back.

23:25.578 --> 23:31.322
<i>♪</i>

23:31.366 --> 23:33.324
Hi, Mrs. Devers?

23:33.368 --> 23:34.935
We got Sam's CT results,

23:34.978 --> 23:36.589
and he's gonna need
another procedure

23:36.632 --> 23:38.460
to stop the bleed.

23:38.504 --> 23:40.854
Uh, do whatever you have to.

23:40.897 --> 23:43.552
Actually, uh,
we do need to make a choice.

23:43.596 --> 23:47.121
And since Sam is intubated,
the decision falls to you.

23:48.731 --> 23:51.386
Please, have a seat.

23:51.430 --> 23:55.869
So we can do a thoracotomy
and fix the vessel,

23:55.912 --> 23:57.827
but it is a major procedure

23:57.871 --> 24:00.003
that comes
with some significant risks.

24:00.047 --> 24:02.789
Or we can place a stent,

24:02.832 --> 24:04.747
which is
a much less invasive procedure,

24:04.791 --> 24:06.488
but it does mean
Sam would have to be

24:06.532 --> 24:09.360
on anticoagulants
for the rest of his life.

24:09.404 --> 24:10.840
[sighs]

24:10.884 --> 24:12.625
It could result in him
being pulled from active duty.

24:12.668 --> 24:16.237
He could still work,
just not on the street, right?

24:16.280 --> 24:18.413
Yes.

24:18.457 --> 24:21.590
Mrs. Devers, this is
a very big decision

24:21.634 --> 24:24.550
that could potentially end
your husband's career.

24:24.593 --> 24:27.466
So if you need more time,
or if you have any--

24:27.509 --> 24:32.601
No.
I'd like you to do the stent.

24:32.645 --> 24:33.994
[sighs]
Okay.

24:37.214 --> 24:41.001
- How's it looking?
- Almost there. You?

24:41.044 --> 24:42.306
Still not clotting.

24:42.350 --> 24:44.352
Uh, keep up the FFP,
cryo, and blood.

24:44.395 --> 24:45.832
More lap pads.

24:45.875 --> 24:47.747
All right, uterine incision.

24:47.790 --> 24:50.532
[monitor beeping]

24:53.013 --> 24:55.842
There we go.

24:55.885 --> 25:00.455
Here she comes.
Here comes baby.

25:00.499 --> 25:03.763
All right.
Got her.

25:03.806 --> 25:05.068
Here she is.

25:05.112 --> 25:07.506
All right. Apgar, 6.

25:10.900 --> 25:12.989
Baby needs to be intubated.

25:13.033 --> 25:14.687
I'm on it.

25:14.730 --> 25:16.253
Still got a lot
of bleeding here.

25:16.297 --> 25:18.255
Uterus is still bleeding too.

25:18.299 --> 25:22.042
Pressure's down to 82/54.

25:22.085 --> 25:23.826
I'm in.
Let's get her up to the NICU.

25:23.870 --> 25:25.567
[monitors beeping]

25:25.611 --> 25:26.960
Kat's hemorrhaging.

25:27.003 --> 25:29.571
All right, I need
2 milligrams methergine IM,

25:29.615 --> 25:32.966
250 micrograms hemabate subQ.
Get me a Bakri.

25:33.009 --> 25:34.533
Keep up the leverage.

25:34.576 --> 25:37.274
She's bleeding from her nose.
She's in DIC.

25:37.318 --> 25:39.407
If she can't clot,
her liver's never gonna hold.

25:39.450 --> 25:41.583
Down to 70/42.

25:41.627 --> 25:43.193
Crockett?

25:43.237 --> 25:47.458
Yeah, her liver's ruptured.
Curve six, let's go.

25:47.502 --> 25:49.243
She's bleeding out.
I need more blood!

25:55.597 --> 25:58.121
- Easy, guys.
- What--

25:58.165 --> 25:59.862
- no, K--
- Kat?

25:59.906 --> 26:02.865
Wait, wait, wait, wait.
Where are you taking her?

26:02.909 --> 26:05.172
Her liver ruptured.
We're trying to stop the bleed.

26:05.215 --> 26:06.390
What?

26:06.434 --> 26:07.957
Mrs. Miller?
This is Dr. Blake,

26:08.001 --> 26:09.916
chief of our
transplant surgery.

26:09.959 --> 26:11.482
We believe
that your daughter's gonna need

26:11.526 --> 26:13.441
a liver transplant.
- A transplant?

26:13.484 --> 26:14.747
A section of liver,

26:14.790 --> 26:16.052
ideally from a living donor.

26:16.096 --> 26:17.663
For now, we're gonna take her
to the ICU

26:17.706 --> 26:21.362
and get her stabilized
until we can find a match.

26:21.405 --> 26:23.669
We'll keep you updated, okay?

26:23.712 --> 26:26.410
Use me. I'm ready.

26:26.454 --> 26:27.760
Well, there's
a process to this--

26:27.803 --> 26:30.023
My daughter is not waiting.

26:30.066 --> 26:31.938
I am the same blood type,
I'm healthy,

26:31.981 --> 26:33.983
and I'm standing
right in front of you.

26:34.027 --> 26:36.029
And I am not leaving
until I can make sure

26:36.072 --> 26:38.248
that my daughter lives
to see her baby.

26:38.292 --> 26:40.468
<i>[tense music]</i>

26:40.511 --> 26:42.992
Okay.

26:48.955 --> 26:51.653
<i>[applause]</i>

26:51.697 --> 26:54.090
<i>Hi, I'm Lydia Reed.</i>

26:54.134 --> 26:55.614
<i>And this is an issue</i>

26:55.657 --> 26:57.703
<i>that many of us parents</i> <i>
deal with.</i>

26:57.746 --> 27:00.531
<i>Because we value the truth.</i>

27:00.575 --> 27:02.316
<i>But what we value even more</i>

27:02.359 --> 27:05.580
<i>is our children's</i> <i>
happiness and safety.</i>

27:05.624 --> 27:08.583
<i>So what happens</i> <i>
when those two values</i>

27:08.627 --> 27:10.106
<i>come into conflict?</i>

27:10.150 --> 27:12.065
<i>We know something</i> <i>
that's gonna hurt our kids.</i>

27:12.108 --> 27:15.634
<i>So what do we do?</i> <i>
We put it aside.</i>

27:15.677 --> 27:17.984
<i>When you find something</i> <i>
that you...</i>

27:18.027 --> 27:20.464
Okay, halfway
through the IVC anastomosis.

27:20.508 --> 27:22.118
How're we looking, Marty?

27:22.162 --> 27:24.033
Losing too much blood.

27:24.077 --> 27:26.340
Pressure's down to 84/56.

27:26.383 --> 27:28.124
Come on.

27:28.168 --> 27:29.256
Check that liver again.

27:29.299 --> 27:32.607
[monitor beeping]

27:34.914 --> 27:36.916
Yeah, I got another bleeder.

27:36.959 --> 27:38.352
Maya, buzz me.

27:38.395 --> 27:43.139
Right there, go. Okay.

27:43.183 --> 27:46.577
Damn it. Another bleeder.

27:46.621 --> 27:48.667
And another.

27:48.710 --> 27:49.711
Dr. Blake, I could use
another set of hands.

27:49.755 --> 27:50.930
<i>No, I can't.</i>

27:50.973 --> 27:52.975
- Pamela-- <i>
- I want the best outcome</i>

27:53.019 --> 27:54.281
<i>for that woman's daughter,</i> <i>
Crockett,</i>

27:54.324 --> 27:56.500
<i>and right now that's you.</i>

27:56.544 --> 27:58.328
<i>Just focus on finishing</i> <i>
the anastomosis.</i>

27:58.372 --> 27:59.852
All right, but she's losing
a lot of blood.

27:59.895 --> 28:02.985
<i>You can do this.</i> <i>
Stop chasing the bleeding.</i>

28:03.029 --> 28:04.552
77/48.

28:04.595 --> 28:05.771
<i>The faster you sew</i> <i>
that vessel,</i>

28:05.814 --> 28:07.250
<i>the sooner you can get</i> <i>
out of there.</i>

28:07.294 --> 28:09.513
All right.

28:09.557 --> 28:11.385
Finishing the anastomosis.

28:11.428 --> 28:13.735
[alarm beeping]
- 72/40.

28:13.779 --> 28:15.868
- Hold on.
- MAPs are in the 50s.

28:15.911 --> 28:17.130
Hold on!

28:17.173 --> 28:19.741
[alarm beeping]

28:19.785 --> 28:22.831
Easy. Easy, easy. Okay, got it.

28:22.875 --> 28:24.746
Cut me.

28:24.790 --> 28:26.792
How're we looking?

28:26.835 --> 28:28.315
Pressure stabilized.

28:28.358 --> 28:29.751
All right.

28:29.795 --> 28:32.101
Let's get this belly tied up
and get out of here.

28:32.145 --> 28:36.845
<i>♪</i>

28:36.889 --> 28:39.718
So we've written down
a few sentences here.

28:39.761 --> 28:42.459
Would you mind reading them
out loud for us?

28:42.503 --> 28:45.288
Sure.
[clears throat]

28:47.029 --> 28:49.075
[haltingly]
"When you find something

28:49.118 --> 28:51.251
"you don't want
to tell your kids,

28:51.294 --> 28:53.557
"that's usually the thing

28:53.601 --> 28:57.126
you need
to tell them the most."

28:57.170 --> 28:59.781
This was from a talk
I gave a few years ago.

28:59.825 --> 29:03.306
Yeah, five to be exact.

29:03.350 --> 29:06.005
I have it right here.

29:06.048 --> 29:07.310
<i>[speaking clearly]</i> <i>
When you find something</i>

29:07.354 --> 29:09.530
<i>that you don't want</i> <i>
to tell your kids,</i>

29:09.573 --> 29:10.836
<i>that's usually the thing</i>

29:10.879 --> 29:12.838
<i>that you need</i> <i>
to tell them the most.</i>

29:12.881 --> 29:16.189
<i>That's the thing</i> <i>
they need to he--</i>

29:16.232 --> 29:17.625
I'm hearing
a marked difference

29:17.668 --> 29:19.366
in your speech pattern
on the video.

29:19.409 --> 29:24.284
It's not as halting
or pressured as it is now.

29:24.327 --> 29:26.765
Is that significant?

29:26.808 --> 29:28.288
I think it could be.

29:28.331 --> 29:30.812
And these outbursts of yours,
they're sudden.

29:30.856 --> 29:33.075
They're often unwarranted.
- Yes.

29:33.119 --> 29:36.035
It's called
Pseudobulbar Affect.

29:36.078 --> 29:37.297
What's--

29:37.340 --> 29:39.908
They're exaggerated
emotional responses.

29:39.952 --> 29:41.780
They're not caused
by emotional instability

29:41.823 --> 29:45.609
or an altered
psychological state.

29:45.653 --> 29:47.742
Um, they're caused
by the degeneration

29:47.786 --> 29:49.309
of certain brain cells.

29:49.352 --> 29:51.137
I'm really sorry to have
to tell you this, Lydia,

29:51.180 --> 29:54.227
but I think that we might
be dealing with ALS.

29:54.270 --> 29:55.706
ALS?

29:55.750 --> 29:59.058
No, no. It c--can't be.

29:59.101 --> 30:01.974
The neurologist ruled it out.

30:02.017 --> 30:05.978
I imagine that they ruled out
a more common presentation.

30:06.021 --> 30:07.588
- I--
- I think that you have a more rare form

30:07.631 --> 30:09.068
which is called Bulbar ALS.

30:09.111 --> 30:11.331
Much more difficult
to diagnose.

30:11.374 --> 30:13.768
<i>[apprehensive music]</i>

30:13.812 --> 30:15.988
I definitely have it?

30:16.031 --> 30:17.250
I have a really strong hunch

30:17.293 --> 30:19.121
that that's
what we're dealing with here.

30:19.165 --> 30:26.128
<i>♪</i>

30:27.129 --> 30:30.611
[laughing]

30:30.654 --> 30:32.874
Lydia?

30:32.918 --> 30:36.660
I mean, I'm sad.

30:38.575 --> 30:44.494
- But I'm--I'm--
- I'm relieved.

30:44.538 --> 30:47.846
ALS was my greatest fear.

30:49.848 --> 30:52.807
But at least I finally have--

30:52.851 --> 30:54.678
at least I finally have
an answer.

30:54.722 --> 30:57.072
Right?

31:01.642 --> 31:03.818
Ethan.

31:03.862 --> 31:06.081
I've been thinking
about it, man.

31:06.125 --> 31:08.692
Sam would want the thoracotomy.

31:08.736 --> 31:10.912
That's what
he should be getting.

31:10.956 --> 31:12.871
Well, look,
I've been looking

31:12.914 --> 31:15.047
over the bodycam footage.
I got an idea.

31:16.526 --> 31:17.963
Mrs. Devers,

31:18.006 --> 31:19.747
Sam's procedure
hasn't started yet,

31:19.790 --> 31:22.358
but I was hoping we could talk.

31:25.492 --> 31:27.929
My dad's a cop, my sister.

31:27.973 --> 31:31.237
Before I did this, I was too.

31:31.280 --> 31:33.500
And even though
I'm not anymore,

31:33.543 --> 31:36.677
every time I hear sirens go by,

31:36.720 --> 31:38.244
I wish I was in that car.

31:40.507 --> 31:43.597
It's a part of who I am.

31:43.640 --> 31:46.426
It's a part of who Sam is too.

31:48.558 --> 31:51.039
We wanted to show you
what happened today

31:51.083 --> 31:54.564
after your husband was shot.

31:54.608 --> 31:57.045
This might be difficult.

31:57.089 --> 32:00.440
But we think it's important
you see it.

32:00.483 --> 32:03.878
Okay?
- Okay.

32:06.576 --> 32:07.882
<i>Get on the ground!</i>

32:07.926 --> 32:09.405
<i>You all right, Sam?</i>

32:09.449 --> 32:10.972
<i>Alice. Alice!</i>

32:11.016 --> 32:11.930
<i>Stay here, stay here.</i> <i>
- Call Alice.</i>

32:11.973 --> 32:13.322
<i>10-1, 10-1!</i>

32:13.366 --> 32:14.715
<i>- Alice.</i> <i>
- Shots fired, shots fired!</i>

32:14.758 --> 32:16.499
<i>- Call Alice.</i> <i>
- Roll an ambo!</i>

32:16.543 --> 32:18.893
<i>- Stay with me, Sam.</i> <i>
- Call my wife. Call Alice.</i>

32:18.937 --> 32:21.330
<i>Stay with me, Sam.</i>

32:21.374 --> 32:25.073
[weeping]

32:27.641 --> 32:31.558
He wanted you, Mrs. Devers.
He was calling for you.

32:31.601 --> 32:35.475
- No one else.
- Yes.

32:35.518 --> 32:39.609
Alice, I know this is
very tough for you.

32:39.653 --> 32:41.394
But we still have time.

32:41.437 --> 32:44.440
Are you sure you want
to do the stent?

32:47.356 --> 32:51.230
Or we can switch
to the thoracotomy.

32:51.273 --> 32:54.189
We believe
that's what Sam would want.

32:57.366 --> 32:59.934
[breathes shakily]

33:01.849 --> 33:03.329
Do the thoracotomy.

33:23.523 --> 33:27.962
My CT's clear.
You ready to go?

33:28.006 --> 33:29.920
That deserves
some celebration.

33:29.964 --> 33:31.183
That'd be nice.

33:31.226 --> 33:34.664
<i>[pensive music]</i>

33:34.708 --> 33:37.580
<i>♪</i>

33:37.624 --> 33:41.497
- Here she is.
- Oh, my God.

33:43.543 --> 33:46.372
I can't believe
she's really here.

33:46.415 --> 33:51.725
Oh, look at her.
She's perfect.

33:51.768 --> 33:53.814
She's so tiny.

33:55.903 --> 33:58.253
Am I gonna be able
to take care of her?

33:58.297 --> 34:01.952
You will. I know you will.

34:01.996 --> 34:08.916
<i>♪</i>

34:14.226 --> 34:17.272
Hey, listen, about before--

34:17.316 --> 34:20.884
I have been treating you
like you need saving.

34:20.928 --> 34:23.061
I'm sorry about that.

34:23.104 --> 34:26.977
Look, I know it wasn't
coming from a bad place, Will.

34:27.021 --> 34:29.328
Okay.

34:29.371 --> 34:31.808
Does mean that,
as your landlord,

34:31.852 --> 34:33.506
I'm gonna need
the rent tomorrow.

34:33.549 --> 34:37.640
Oh, well, actually,
I can do you one better.

34:37.684 --> 34:41.949
I, um, picked it up
during lunch today.

34:44.517 --> 34:46.867
- Thanks.
- Mm-hmm.

34:55.180 --> 34:58.661
She's set up with Dr. Abrams
for a full consultation.

34:58.705 --> 35:00.185
You know, a couple
of pretty exciting

35:00.228 --> 35:01.577
clinical trials out there.

35:01.621 --> 35:05.494
Between those, current meds,
PT, speech therapy,

35:05.538 --> 35:07.496
there's actually quite a lot
we can do for her.

35:07.540 --> 35:09.324
You know, I wanted to look up
that talk you used

35:09.368 --> 35:11.500
about the truth
and being a better parent,

35:11.544 --> 35:14.329
but it was really far down
on the list.

35:14.373 --> 35:16.375
I'm just curious
why you picked that one.

35:18.159 --> 35:20.379
I don't know.
Good question.

35:20.422 --> 35:22.424
Looked, uh--looked interesting?

35:22.468 --> 35:29.605
<i>♪</i>

35:34.044 --> 35:38.875
- Hey.
- Nice job today.

35:38.919 --> 35:39.963
Thanks.

35:44.316 --> 35:47.580
Hey, look, if it, uh--
[clears throat]

35:47.623 --> 35:51.061
If it felt like I crossed--
- I scheduled my disc surgery.

35:51.105 --> 35:52.237
Oh.

35:54.630 --> 35:57.242
I was concerned
about leaving my patients

35:57.285 --> 35:59.418
for a few weeks, but...

36:01.507 --> 36:04.205
I see now they'll be fine.

36:04.249 --> 36:11.430
<i>♪</i>

36:20.395 --> 36:22.963
That's great.

36:29.970 --> 36:32.581
- Honey, you got a second?
- Yeah.

36:36.019 --> 36:39.980
Something I've been, um,
meaning to talk to you about.

36:40.023 --> 36:41.068
Um...

36:43.636 --> 36:44.985
What's going on? You all right?

36:48.118 --> 36:50.295
Luke broke up with me.

36:50.338 --> 36:52.427
Oh.

36:52.471 --> 36:57.258
And I--
I just really cared.

36:57.302 --> 36:59.434
Honey, I'm so sorry.

36:59.478 --> 37:02.002
I just feel so stupid.

37:02.045 --> 37:03.786
You sure it wasn't,
I don't know,

37:03.830 --> 37:07.050
like, just a--just a fight
or something?

37:07.094 --> 37:08.791
No, it's over.
[sighs]

37:14.101 --> 37:18.975
Didn't you say you wanted
to talk to me about something?

37:19.019 --> 37:20.716
No.

37:20.760 --> 37:22.762
It--it can wait.
- [sniffles]

37:26.287 --> 37:29.464
- Thank you.
- Yeah.

37:29.508 --> 37:31.292
Dr. Archer says he'll be
back on the street

37:31.336 --> 37:34.817
in six weeks.
- Good.

37:34.861 --> 37:37.255
Think she'll be able
to handle it?

37:37.298 --> 37:40.388
I hope so.

37:40.432 --> 37:41.781
At least she knows
a little more

37:41.824 --> 37:43.304
about the person she loves.

37:43.348 --> 37:50.529
<i>♪</i>

37:54.272 --> 37:56.448
- - Will, the Vas-
- COM trial,

37:56.491 --> 37:59.277
please tell me
you're not gonna testify.

37:59.320 --> 38:01.322
- I am.
- Don't.

38:01.366 --> 38:03.063
These people will do anything
to protect themselves.

38:03.106 --> 38:06.501
You don't know
what they're capable of.

38:06.545 --> 38:08.155
I have to.

38:08.198 --> 38:11.201
Then what about me?
You're gonna ruin my life.

38:11.245 --> 38:12.681
They're gonna throw me in jail.

38:12.725 --> 38:15.597
Jessa, let go of me.
Let go of me!

38:15.641 --> 38:18.644
Dr. Halstead,
is there a problem?

38:18.687 --> 38:21.342
<i>[uneasy music]</i>

38:21.386 --> 38:28.523
<i>♪</i>

38:39.317 --> 38:42.407
- Dylan.
- Oh, Milena.

38:45.932 --> 38:48.064
- [exhales]
- Thank God, you're safe.

38:48.108 --> 38:51.024
Come here.

38:51.067 --> 38:53.679
So some--
some gang members got away.

38:53.722 --> 38:56.551
I'm afraid there's a mole
in CPD who tipped them off.

38:56.595 --> 38:59.554
If there is...

38:59.598 --> 39:01.817
I've been made.

39:01.861 --> 39:03.732
That's why you had the money.

39:03.776 --> 39:05.168
In case you had
to get off the grid.

39:05.212 --> 39:07.127
Yeah, and I need to.

39:09.956 --> 39:12.350
Listen, it--it's too
dangerous to stay with me,

39:12.393 --> 39:15.396
but I have a friend
who's fixing up a building.

39:15.440 --> 39:17.267
I'm sure you could
hole up there.

39:17.311 --> 39:20.749
Okay, thanks.

39:20.793 --> 39:27.103
Oh, Dylan, my name,
uh, it's Jo.

39:29.889 --> 39:32.674
Come on, Jo.
Let's get you safe.

39:32.718 --> 39:39.028
<i>♪</i>

39:49.038 --> 39:51.301
Ethan?

39:51.345 --> 39:54.522
Come in.
- Thanks.

39:54.566 --> 39:57.743
Um, my dad liked
highland scotch.

39:57.786 --> 40:02.835
I didn't know--
- I do, thanks.

40:02.878 --> 40:04.314
Please.

40:04.358 --> 40:07.013
<i>[sentimental music]</i>

40:07.056 --> 40:14.020
<i>♪</i>

40:14.890 --> 40:18.677
My sister. My nephew.

40:20.722 --> 40:22.681
My first day in the navy.

40:22.724 --> 40:26.728
I felt like you were all
my family too.

40:29.209 --> 40:30.993
50 years.

40:31.037 --> 40:34.649
We had a life together,
but no one could know.

40:34.693 --> 40:37.609
<i>[emotional music]</i>

40:37.652 --> 40:44.790
<i>♪</i>

40:48.228 --> 40:52.928
You a--a scotch man
like your dad?

40:52.972 --> 40:54.800
I am.

40:57.019 --> 40:58.934
Funny story
about a bottle of scotch

40:58.978 --> 41:03.199
your dad and I had in Dubai
after the Gulf War.

41:03.243 --> 41:04.766
You want to hear it?

41:06.551 --> 41:08.509
Yeah, I do.

41:08.553 --> 41:15.603
<i>♪</i>

41:21.304 --> 41:24.264
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

41:24.307 --> 41:31.271
<i>♪</i>

41:51.421 --> 41:54.337
[wolf howls]
